body:
I can't really reproduce the error, for me it opens without any really noticable delay with MetalANGLE + launch storyboard. Maybe my mac is faster? I have a Mac mini M1 2020. Do you maybe have any minimal reproducer project?

> At this time the next view controller needs to be setup already.
Is this documented somewhere? Haven't found anything in the apple docs.

Anyhow, by looking through the docs it seems like there would be nothing speaking against hooking up the controller initialization in the willFinishLaunching event (https://developer.apple.com/documentation/uikit/uiapplicationdelegate/1623032-application?language=objc). Would you be able to test, whether this fixes the issue for you?

> The ApplicationListener.create() method as well as the completion of the OpenGL setup are called **after** didFinishLaunching().

As far as I understand it, not precisly. They are called during the "didFinishLaunching" callback. Also, according to the docs, "This method is called after state restoration has occurred but before your app’s window and other UI have been presented. At some point after this method returns, the system calls another of your app delegate’s methods to move the app to the active (foreground) state or the background state." 
https://developer.apple.com/documentation/uikit/uiapplicationdelegate/1622921-application?language=objc
So the app seems to be not expected to have something already drawn, at this point.

But interesting in the code is also this:
```java
	public void viewWillAppear (boolean arg0) {
		super.viewWillAppear(arg0);
		// start GLKViewController even though we may only draw a single frame
		// (we may be in non-continuous mode)
		setPaused(false);
	}
```
So maybe "setPaused" was working different in GLKit than in MGLKit? But thats also just a random idea, can't test around without being able to reproduce it.

The ApplicationListener.create() method is called during the first draw call of the view controller:

IOSGraphics.java
```
	public void draw (GLKView view, CGRect rect) {
		...
		if (!created) {
			// OpenGL glViewport() function expects backbuffer coordinates instead of logical coordinates
			gl20.glViewport(0, 0, screenBounds.backBufferWidth, screenBounds.backBufferHeight);

			String versionString = gl20.glGetString(GL20.GL_VERSION);
			String vendorString = gl20.glGetString(GL20.GL_VENDOR);
			String rendererString = gl20.glGetString(GL20.GL_RENDERER);
			glVersion = new GLVersion(Application.ApplicationType.iOS, versionString, vendorString, rendererString);

			updateSafeInsets();
			app.listener.create();
			app.listener.resize(getWidth(), getHeight());
			created = true;
		}
		...
```
I managed to move all that stuff into the didFinishLaunching method in a local fork to make:

IOSApplication.java
```
	final boolean didFinishLaunching (UIApplication uiApp, UIApplicationLaunchOptions options) {
		...
		this.uiWindow.setRootViewController(this.graphics.viewController);
		this.graphics.updateSafeInsets();
		
		Gdx.app.debug("IOSApplication", "created");

		// make sure the OpenGL view has contents before displaying it
		this.graphics.view.display();

		return true;
	}
```

This entirely removes the black/empty frames after the launch screen. The bigger the app is the longer this "blackout" was, in my case over 500ms. However it is still noticeable in the default libGDX app. 
I'm providing a PR with this fix.

issue.body:
#### Issue details

I've been facing an issue on iOS only when using `FrameBuffer`. When I ported my game [October Bro](https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=de.bsautermeister.jump) from Android/Desktop to iOS, I noticed that my game screen was just black (or just the screen-clear color I used).

After longer investigation and digging into the LibGdx code, I could figure out the problem, and come up with a workaround. And my hope is that this issue report turns into a simple fix PR (either by me or by you), so that my workaround will not be needed anymore.

#### Reproduction steps/code

Use the following code on iOS, and toggle the `FIX` flag.

```java
public class MyGdxGame extends ApplicationAdapter {

	private static final boolean FIX = true; // <-- please toggle me! :)

	SpriteBatch batch;
	Texture img;

	FrameBuffer frameBuffer;

	OrthographicCamera camera;

	boolean created = false;

	@Override
	public void create () {
		batch = new SpriteBatch();
		img = new Texture("badlogic.jpg");

		camera = new OrthographicCamera();

		created = true;
		frameBuffer = new FrameBuffer(Pixmap.Format.RGBA8888, Gdx.graphics.getWidth(), Gdx.graphics.getHeight(), false);
	}

	@Override
	public void render () {
		Gdx.gl.glClearColor(1f, 0f, 0f, 1);
		Gdx.gl.glClear(GL20.GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT);

		IntBuffer oldFbo = BufferUtils.newIntBuffer(1);
		Gdx.gl.glGetIntegerv(GL_FRAMEBUFFER_BINDING, oldFbo);

		frameBuffer.begin();

		Gdx.gl.glClearColor(0f, 1f, 1f, 1);
		Gdx.gl.glClear(GL20.GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT);

		camera.setToOrtho(true, frameBuffer.getWidth(), frameBuffer.getHeight());
		camera.update();

		Gdx.gl.glClearColor(1.0f, 1.0f, 1.0f, 255 / 255.0f);

		batch.begin();
		batch.draw(img, 0, 0);
		batch.end();

		frameBuffer.end();

		if (FIX) {
			// use the previous back buffer index, instead of defaultFramebufferHandle from GLFrameBuffer#unbind()
			int fboIdx = oldFbo.get();
			Gdx.gl.glBindFramebuffer(GL_FRAMEBUFFER, fboIdx);
		}

		camera.setToOrtho(true, Gdx.graphics.getWidth(), Gdx.graphics.getHeight());
		camera.update();

		// render pixel-art buffer to screen
		batch.setProjectionMatrix(camera.combined);
		batch.begin();
		batch.draw(frameBuffer.getColorBufferTexture(),
				0, 0, 0, 0, Gdx.graphics.getWidth() / 2f, Gdx.graphics.getHeight() / 2f, 1f, 1f, 0f, 0, 0,
				frameBuffer.getWidth(), frameBuffer.getHeight(), false, true);
		batch.end();
	}

	@Override
	public void dispose () {
		img.dispose();
		batch.dispose();
		if (frameBuffer != null) {
			frameBuffer.dispose();
		}
	}
}
```

The problematic code seems to come from the following section, which seems to even try to exactly this iOS specific problem according to the comment:
https://github.com/libgdx/libgdx/blob/9036b801cc3f4844d346dc96bf9b8f89d8390ad0/gdx/src/com/badlogic/gdx/graphics/glutils/GLFrameBuffer.java#L128-L138

However, while testing and debugging this, I could observe the following:
- As written in these lines, the screen is always `fboIdx = defaultFramebufferHandle = 0` on Desktop/Android, but usually `fboIdx = 1` on iOS
- However, that might depend on the game. Or on the point in time when the `new FrameBuffer(...)` constructor is called for the first time. I observed on my single iOS game that the very first time the constructor is called, that the stored fboIndex is first `0`, and later it would be `1` on iOS.
- The fact that via the static `defaultFramebufferHandleInitialized` the initialization of the `defaultFramebufferHandle` is only done once causes the problem that we **might try to go back to the wrong index** on `FrameBuffer#end()`. As shown in the above code example.

#### TL;DR Workaround

Summarizing my current workaround in a brief from above, the problem can be prevented by wrapping the `frameBuffer` begin/end function with:

```java

IntBuffer oldFbo = BufferUtils.newIntBuffer(1);
Gdx.gl.glGetIntegerv(GL_FRAMEBUFFER_BINDING, oldFbo);

frameBuffer.begin();
// ...
frameBuffer.end();

int fboIdx = oldFbo.get();
Gdx.gl.glBindFramebuffer(GL_FRAMEBUFFER, fboIdx);
```

To kind of override the internal behavior of how `FrameBuffer#end()` does the unbind to go back to the screen.

#### Version of libGDX and/or relevant dependencies
`gdxVersion = '1.12.0'`

#### Screenshots

With both `FIX=false` or `FIX=true`, there is no problem on Android/Desktop:

<img width="752" alt="Screenshot 2023-12-09 at 1 33 23 PM" src="https://github.com/libgdx/libgdx/assets/2537736/c662a250-3005-430d-b88e-0f690b816738">

However, on iOS, using `FIX=false` causes a wrong result:

![Simulator Screenshot - iPhone 15 - 2023-12-09 at 13 32 31](https://github.com/libgdx/libgdx/assets/2537736/8e6f218d-fac8-452f-8174-57bc1cea2342)

The reason is that `FrameBuffer#end()` does **not** work as expected.

With my fix to enforce going back to the previous frame buffer (here: the screen), it works correctly on **any** platform, even iOS:

![Simulator Screenshot - iPhone 15 - 2023-12-09 at 13 33 00](https://github.com/libgdx/libgdx/assets/2537736/0356d594-f55a-428d-bf69-f36610610cf3)

#### Please select the affected platforms
- [ ] Android
- [x] iOS
- [ ] HTML/GWT
- [ ] Windows
- [ ] Linux
- [ ] macOS

#### References:

- [FBO bug in Cocos2D](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/11617013/why-would-glbindframebuffergl-framebuffer-0-result-in-blank-screen-in-cocos2d)
